terraform Block Structure ->

⭐ 1. terraform block
This block tells Terraform which required providers or versions to use.
Example:

terraform {
  required_version = ">= 1.0"
  
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~> 5.0"
    }
  }
}
📌 Purpose:
	• Define Terraform version
	• Download provider plugins
	• Maintain consistency

⭐ 2. provider block
This block tells which cloud you are using and any authentication details.
Example:

provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}
📌 Purpose:
	• Select cloud provider
	• Configure region/credentials
	• Needed before creating resources

⭐ 3. resource block
This is the main block where you create actual cloud resources.
Example:

resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  ami           = "ami-0e670eb768a5fc3d4"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"

  tags = {
    Name = "MyEC2"
  }
}
📌 Purpose:
	• Create EC2, VPC, RDS, S3, etc.
	• Each resource has a type + name
	• Contains required properties

🎯 Full Example (All Block Structure)

terraform {
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~> 5.0"
    }
  }
}

provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}

resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  ami           = "ami-0e670eb768a5fc3d4"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"

  tags = {
    Name = "Terraform-EC2"
  }
}

🎉 Easy One-Line Explanation
terraform → settings
provider → where to create infra
resource → what to create

✅ What is a variable block in Terraform?
The variable block is used to define input values that you can reuse in your Terraform configuration.
➡ Helps avoid hardcoding
➡ Makes templates reusable
➡ Lets you override values during apply

⭐ Basic Variable Block Example

variable "instance_type" {
  type        = string
  default     = "t2.micro"
  description = "EC2 instance type"
}
Usage in a resource:

resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  ami           = "ami-0e670eb768a5fc3d4"
  instance_type = var.instance_type
}

⭐ Types of Variables
1️⃣ string

variable "env" { 
  type    = string 
  default = "dev" 
}
2️⃣ number

variable "instance_count" { 
  type    = number 
  default = 2 
}
3️⃣ bool

variable "enable_monitoring" { 
  type    = bool 
  default = true 
}
4️⃣ list

variable "subnets" {
  type    = list(string)
  default = ["subnet-1", "subnet-2"]
}
5️⃣ map

variable "tags" {
  type = map(string)
  default = {
    Name = "MyServer"
    Env  = "Dev"
  }
}

⭐ How to use variable values?
From command line:

terraform apply -var "instance_type=m5.large"
From tfvars file
File: terraform.tfvars

instance_type = "t3.micro"
Apply:

terraform apply

⭐ Full Example Using Variables
variables.tf

variable "instance_type" {
  type        = string
  default     = "t2.micro"
}

variable "ami_id" {
  type = string
}
main.tf

resource "aws_instance" "server" {
  ami           = var.ami_id
  instance_type = var.instance_type
}
terraform.tfvars

ami_id = "ami-0e670eb768a5fc3d4"

🎯 Simple Explanation
Variable block = place where you declare inputs
var.xyz = how you use those inputs


✅ What is an Output Block?
An output block is used to display values after Terraform finishes creating resources.
It helps you see important information like:
	• EC2 Public IP
	• VPC ID
	• S3 Bucket Name
	• Load Balancer DNS
	• IAM Role ARN

⭐ Basic Output Block Example

output "instance_public_ip" {
  value = aws_instance.my_ec2.public_ip
}
After you run:

terraform apply
You will see something like:

instance_public_ip = "13.234.44.21"

⭐ Another Example (VPC ID)

output "vpc_id" {
  value = aws_vpc.my_vpc.id
}

⭐ Output With Description

output "ec2_ip" {
  description = "Public IP of the EC2 instance"
  value       = aws_instance.server.public_ip
}

⭐ Output Sensitive Value (password, keys)
To hide the output:

output "db_password" {
  value     = var.db_password
  sensitive = true
}
Terraform will not print the real value.

⭐ Output That Depends on List
Example: Output all subnet IDs

output "subnet_ids" {
  value = aws_subnet.public[*].id
}

⭐ Full Example
main.tf

resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  ami           = "ami-0e670eb768a5fc3d4"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"
}
outputs.tf

output "ec2_public_ip" {
  value       = aws_instance.my_ec2.public_ip
  description = "Public IP of EC2"
}

🎯 Simple Explanation
📌 Variable block = input
📌 Output block = output
You give inputs → Terraform creates infra → Terraform shows outputs


✅ What is a Data Block in Terraform?
A data block is used to read or fetch existing information from cloud resources without creating them.
➡ Terraform resource = creates new things
➡ Terraform data = reads existing things

⭐ Why do we use data blocks?
	• To fetch an existing VPC
	• To get the latest AMI
	• To fetch existing subnets
	• To get IAM roles
	• To read S3 buckets
	• To fetch security groups

⭐ Basic Data Block Example (Fetch Latest AMI)

data "aws_ami" "ubuntu" {
  most_recent = true

  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd/ubuntu-focal-20.04-amd64-server-*"]
  }

  owners = ["099720109477"] # Canonical Ubuntu owner ID
}
Use it in a resource:

resource "aws_instance" "server" {
  ami           = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
  instance_type = "t2.micro"
}

⭐ Example: Get Existing VPC

data "aws_vpc" "default" {
  default = true
}
Use it:

resource "aws_subnet" "public" {
  vpc_id            = data.aws_vpc.default.id
  cidr_block        = "10.0.1.0/24"
}

⭐ Example: Fetch Existing Subnets

data "aws_subnets" "all" {}
Use:

output "all_subnets" {
  value = data.aws_subnets.all.ids
}

⭐ Example: Fetch Existing Security Group

data "aws_security_group" "sg" {
  name = "default"
}
Use:

resource "aws_instance" "server" {
  ami                    = "ami-0e670eb768a5fc3d4"
  instance_type          = "t2.micro"
  vpc_security_group_ids = [data.aws_security_group.sg.id]
}

⭐ Example: Fetch S3 Bucket Info

data "aws_s3_bucket" "mybucket" {
  bucket = "my-existing-bucket-123"
}

⭐ Full Simple Example
data.tf

data "aws_ami" "ubuntu" {
  most_recent = true
  owners      = ["099720109477"]

  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["ubuntu/images/*"]
  }
}
main.tf

resource "aws_instance" "server" {
  ami           = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
  instance_type = "t2.micro"
}

🎯 Simple Explanation (1 Line)
Resource = create something
Data = read something already created



